The elemental composition of both CNTs was evaluated using XPS analysis (Fig. 5
                        ). The amine and amide functional groups in N-SWCNTs were confirmed by the presence of the N1s peak, whereas no N1s peak was observed in C-SWCNTs. The N1s peak in N-SWCNTs was further deconvoluted into three peaks attributed to primary amine (CH2
                        NH2), amide (NH(CO)), and secondary amine (NHCH2
                        ) groups at 399.8, 400.5, and 401.6 eV, respectively, which agrees well with the results reported by Ma et al., who prepared amino-functionalized CNTs by coupling carboxylic groups on the CNTs with organic amine (Ma et al., 2010).

Under sunlight irradiation, oxygen quenches the CNTs' excited triplet state through the formation of singlet oxygen. Furfuryl alcohol (FFA) was used as a probe to determine the production of 1O2, as 1O2 generation kinetics was indicated by the degradation of 0.2 mM FFA (Fig. 7
                        ). Blank tests performed in the absence of CNTs showed a negligible photolysis of FFA (<2%); after the first 10 h of solar irradiation, no FFA loss was observed in the dark control samples within the experiment's duration. For the N-SWCNT suspensions, the singlet oxygen steady-state concentration ([1O2]ss) (1.3 × 10−12 M) is about three-fold greater than that of the C-SWCNTs (4.1 × 10−13 M). 1O2 production in the CNT suspensions was further confirmed by azide ion (N3¯) quenching. Azide ion quenches 1O2 by the reported second order quenching rate constant of the azide ion (k
                        d (N3¯) = 5 × 108 M−1 s−1) (Haag and Mill, 1987). The rates of FFA loss were suppressed to approximately 60% with the addition of 1 mM of azide, indicating the presence of 1O2 under irradiation.
